TEXT(&beginproblem);
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;
$a=random(1,10,1)*random(-1,1,2);
$b=random(1,10,1)*random(-1,1,2);
$c=random(1,10,1)*random(-1,1,2);

BEGIN_TEXT

$PAR

Why is the following function discontinuous at \(x=-3\)? $PAR

\[ f(x) = \begin{cases}
        \displaystyle \frac{x^2-x-12}{x+3} & \textrm{if }x \neq -3 \\ \\
        1                                  & \textrm{if }x = -3
        \end{cases}\] $PAR

(a) \(f(-3)\) does not exist. $BR
(b) \(\displaystyle \lim_{x \to -3} f(x) \) does not exist (or is infinite). $BR
(c) Both (a) and (b). $BR
(d) \(f(-3)\) and \(\displaystyle \lim_{x \to -3} f(x)\) exist, but they are not equal.

$PAR

 \{ans_rule(10)\}

END_TEXT

ANS(fun_cmp("c", var=>["a","b","c","d"]));

